## Lessons Learned

- **FID-016r2 closed a latent filename collision** between `src-tauri`'s Tauri host crate and `crates/core`'s savant-orig core crate. Both were named `savant_core`, causing `.pdb` + `.rlib` output collisions on `cargo build --workspace`. Renaming `src-tauri`'s lib to `savant_shell` was surgical (3 use-site string replacements in `src-tauri/tests/` + 2 lines already done in earlier partial save = 5 lines of new code). The 241 `savant_core::*` imports across `crates/*` correctly target `crates/core` (distinct workspace crate, `package.name = "savant_core"`, unchanged) — no collateral damage; FID-151 AUDIT grep gate verified (0 in src-tauri/ scope; 241 in crates/* scope untouched).

- **FID-017 §Perfection Loop 5 — full CommonMark + GFM coverage** required `react-markdown` + `remark-gfm` instead of the hand-rolled `MarkdownLite` parser. The hand-rolled parser was 280 lines covering ~6 syntax features; CommonMark + GFM coverage is 97 transitive packages and full coverage of headings (h1-h6), lists (ordered/unordered, nested), code blocks (fenced, indented), tables, task lists, strikethrough, images, links. The +30-40 KB gzipped bundle weight is justified by the maintenance burden of a partial spec parser (LESSON-019 utility-first principle + LAW 13 "build utility, combine overlap"). The `page.tsx` swap was mechanical: import + body. Custom `a` component for external-link security (`rel="noopener noreferrer"`).

- **`useReflections` legacy-key migration block** is the canonical pattern for renaming user data in localStorage without data loss. Reads LEGACY key (one-time) if NEW key is empty; copies; deletes the LEGACY entry. Idempotent (only runs once per user). Pattern reusable across app renames.

- **EVERY FID close-out follows the same audit-trail discipline**: (a) FID body drift correction (status header + Verification checkbox + Resolution § rewrite with status path); (b) §Perfection Loop 5 insertion for iterative corrections made after the FID body was first authored; (c) CHANGELOG [Unreleased] row insertion (between the previous release entry and the next release transition section); (d) FID file move to `dev/fids/archive/` (auto-archive per ECHO §FID Auto-Archive); (e) session summary authored with Work-Matches-Doc re-read + tsc/build-green notes + Perfection Loop summary table. This is the canonical close-out pass for any FID reaching `closed` status.

- **Forward-effective cross-links in FID-doc close-outs** — when a FID close-out cross-references a non-yet-authored follow-up FID (e.g., FID-016 cross-linking to FID-016r2 doc; FID-017 §Perfection Loop 5 referencing react-markdown + remark-gfm package versions), the resolution is forward-effective (the package was installed in the same session but the FID doc hasn't been authored). Per LESSON-016 Draft-and-Prove Rule, this should carry an `[UNVERIFIED-FID-CITE]` marker OR the follow-up FID doc should be authored first. Resolution path is clear (FID-016r2 doc authorship is a separate todo; recommended before v0.0.4 ships).

- **Application build target** — Next.js 15 `output: "export"` makes `?raw` imports for `.md` files the canonical pattern for build-time file embedding. The `next.config.mjs` webpack rule `{ test: /\.md$/, type: "asset/source" }` + `src/types/raw.d.ts` global `declare module "*?raw"` ambient is the durable pattern. The alternative (`fetch("/api/soul")` runtime route) was rejected at the start because `output: "export"` blocks dynamic runtime routes.

- **Tauri runtime guard pattern** — `if ("__TAURI_INTERNALS__" in window)` is the canonical single-source-of-truth check for "are we in a Tauri webview or a plain browser". Use it before any `fetch()` of Tauri-runtime files (e.g., `workspace-savant/SOUL.md`). Pattern surfaced at `src/lib/hooks/use-reflections.ts` and `src/lib/mock-ipc.ts`. Reusable across `src/lib/runtime.ts::isTauriRuntime()` if a 3rd call-site emerges.

- **`force-static` vs `force-dynamic` with `output: "export"`** — `force-dynamic` is incompatible with static export (throws "cannot be used with output: export"). `force-static` is the correct choice for build-time-baked routes like `/api/env`. Without any dynamic export, Next.js requires `force-static` or `revalidate` to be explicit. Cross-ref: `src/app/api/env/route.ts` (FID-008).

